An Analysis of Video Game Sales and Ratings¶

By Basem Al-Rifai¶

Introduction¶

Video games are a huge part of today's society, from rising popularity in E-Sports to increasing demand for video games for entertainment. Video games have been around for a long time, but only recently have sales really begun to break records. Every year, hundreds of games release, but only few become popular. It seems that every year, the bar on what makes a game "good" is set higher. The current best selling video game is Minecraft, with over 200,000,000 sales worldwide.

So that raises the question of what makes a video game popular? Is it the ratings by critics? Is it the time of year the game relased? Is it the console the game is released on? I will also be analyzing indivual game's completion times to determine if there is a relationship between game length and sales. All of these metrics will be measured by tracking effect on sales as a function of rating, platform, release time of year, developer, publisher, and time to beat. I am hoping to find some kind of trends to see what makes a video game sell well. The challenges associated with finding a trend will be normalizing sales numbers between different years because for example, a game that did extremely well in 2002 would most likely not sell as well as a game that did average in 2016 due to the increasing popularity of video games.

I am expecting to find a strong relationship between developer and sales, even if a game has bad ratings, I expected that a developer with a strong reputation such as EA with a mediocre game will beat a perfect score game from another less known developer (indie). I will form a proper hypothesis after exploratory data analysis.

This tutorial will focus on video games released between 2000 and 2019 in the United States to avoid games with insufficient data and avoid attributing US Ratings (Metacritic) to overseas sales.

The Data¶

Primary Dataset: Video game ratings from Metacritic.com¶

The primary dataset will need to be scraped manually by loading all pages from Metacritic.com and pulling the data from the search page. This will be done using an algorithm by Julius Johnson. The algorithm used can be found here. I made slight modifications to the algorithm so that it collects all data from 2000 to 2021 and added some null checks since it kept crashing. This dataset will be used to the strength of reviews effect on sales. This dataset is complete and has very few missing at random values for games that have no user reviews

The fields of this dataset are:

  • Name - Name of the game
  • Date - Release date of game in the US
  • Platform - Platform of the game (i.e. PC, PS4, XOne, etc.)
  • score - Critic score of the game on a scale from 1-100
  • userscore - Users score the game on a scale from 1-10
  • url - url of game page - will be discarded

Metacritic has their own interesting lists, ranking games between genres and consoles. You can explore their reviews on their website

Tertiary Dataset: Video game sales from Vgchartz¶

This dataset, scraped from Vgchartz in April of 2019, and downloaded from kaggle.com, represents a list of about 11563 unique games on every platform that game released. An issue with this dataset is it's age, going up to only 2019 and not including the latest games, so we cannot measure the effect of COVID-19 on video game sales. I originally intended to scrape the data again using the same algorithm used for this dataset, but as of 07/16/2021, VGChartz is returning a 403 when I attempt to scrape. This dataset will be used to get sales metrics for games and compare them to developer/publisher and completion times (with the other tertiary dataset). Not all developers release video game sales metrics, so a subset of this dataset will be analyzed where the data exists. The missingness of the data is Missing At Random since it is a developers decision to not publicize sales

The fields of this dataset are:

  • Rank - Ranking of overall sales - Will be discarded
  • Name - Name of the game
  • Platform - Platform of the game (i.e. PC, PS4, XOne, etc.)
  • Genre - Genre of the game
  • ESRB Rating - ESRB Rating of the game
  • Publisher - Publisher of the game
  • Developer - Developer of the game
  • Critic Score - Critic score of the game from 10 - Will be discarded in favor of metacritic score
  • User Score - Users score the game from 10 - Will be discarded in favor of metacritic score
  • Total Shipped - Total shipped copies of the game
  • Global_Sales - Total worldwide sales (in millions) - Will be discarded since we are focusing on the U.S.
  • NA_Sales - Sales in North America (in millions)
  • PAL_Sales - Sales in Europe (in millions) - Will be discarded since we are focusing on the U.S.
  • JP_Sales - Sales in Japan (in millions) - Will be discarded since we are focusing on the U.S.
  • Other_Sales - Sales in the rest of the world (in millions) - Will be discarded since we are focusing on the U.S.
  • Year - Year of release of the game - Will be discarded since our primary dataset has it

I chose this dataset because it is the most complete collection of video game sales data online ranging back to 1980 with the Atari 2600. This will allow us to trim down the dataset to our chosen range (2000-2019). The reason I am removing the metacritic scores is because I am going to scrap the latest data from metacritic myself.

A link to the dataset can be found here

Tertiary Dataset: HowLongToBeat.com Completion Times¶

This dataset is the latest of the two, going up to 2020. This dataset includes a lot more games that were NOT published (PC Indie games on sites such as itchio) Due to this, a lot of this dataset will be disregarded since this tutorial is only analyzing published games that have public sales metrics. This dataset will be inner joined into the primary dataset to get time to completion for games to determine if there is an effect on sales. This dataset is has some missing at random entries that cannot have completion times given their nature (multiplayer only, mod, DLC, etc.) These games will be disregarded

The fields of this dataset are:

  • id - Game ID from the website.
  • title - Game name.
  • main_story - Average completion time of 'Main Story' in hours. - Will be discarded in favor of all_styles, which is the average of all completion times
  • main_plus_extras - Average completion time of 'Main + Extras' in hours. - Will be discarded in favor of all_styles, which is the average of all completion times
  • completionist - Average completion time of 'Completionist' in hours. - Will be discarded in favor of all_styles, which is the average of all completion times
  • all_styles - Average completion time of 'All Styles' in hours.
  • coop - Average completion time of 'Co-Op' in hours. - Will be discarded since the dataset is focusing on video games playtime in singleplayer
  • versus - Average completion time of 'Vs.' in hours. - Will be discarded since the dataset is focusing on video games playtime in singleplayer
  • type - Type entry to differentiate DLC/Expansion, Mod, and ROM Hack from regular game entries. - Discarded since it is irrelevant when joined with the primary dataset
  • developers - Comma-space separated list of all developers of an entry. - Will be used for focused analysis of HLTB data
  • publishers - Comma-space separated list of all publishers of an entry. - Will be used for focused analysis of HLTB data
  • platforms - Comma-space separated list of all platforms an entry is available on. - Discarded since Vgchartz has more reliable data
  • genres - Comma-separated list of genres for an entry. - Discarded since Vgchartz has more reliable data
  • release_na - Release date in North America (if available). - Will be used for focused analysis of HLTB data
  • release_eu - Release date in Europe (if available). - Discarded since Vgchartz has more reliable data
  • release_jp - Release date in Japan (if available). - Discarded since Vgchartz has more reliable data

A link to the dataset can be found here

Scraping video game rating data from Metacritic 2000-2021¶

This algorithm from Julius Johnson scrapes all data from metacritic search pages (it does not crawl each link individually so it does not get teriary information such as genre and developer, but that can be joined from the other dataset). It uses pandas and beautifulsoup to scrape the data into a dataframe and saves it as a csv. The only missing data are games that are still pending review, which are not many. I chose this algorithm because it works fairly quickly.

In [ ]:
import requests, csv, pandas as pd, pprint, time
from bs4 import BeautifulSoup
import lxml,html5lib

data_dict = {'name':[], 'date':[], 'platform': [], 'score':[], 'url':[], 'userscore':[]} # Data Structure

def webpage(pageNum,year): #function that navigates the metacritic SRP(Search Results Pages) based on the page number and the year
    url = 'https://www.metacritic.com/browse/games/score/metascore/year/all/filtered?year_selected='+ str(year) +'&distribution=&sort=desc&view=condensed&page='+ str(pageNum)
    userAgent = {'User-agent': 'Mozilla/5.0'}
    response = requests.get(url, headers=userAgent)
    return response

def numberPages(response): # Helper Function that determines how many pages are in a SRP to know how many times to run scrapper function
    soup = BeautifulSoup(response.text, 'html.parser')
    pages = soup.find_all('li', {"class":"page last_page"})
    if (len(pages) > 0):
        pagesCleaned = pages[0].find('a', {"class":"page_num"})
        return (pagesCleaned.text)
    else:
        return ""
    
    

def scrapper(num_loops,content):
    tblnum = 0
    while tblnum < num_loops:
        #get Game name
        table_rows = content[tblnum].find_all('tr')
        for tr in table_rows:
            td = tr.find_all('td')
            for a in td[1].find_all('a', {"class":"title"}):
                data_dict['name'].append(a.find('h3').text)
                #print(a.find('h3').text)

        #get Game release date
        table_rows = content[tblnum].find_all('tr')
        for tr in table_rows:
            td = tr.find_all('td')
            for date in td[1].find_all('span',{"class":""}):
                data_dict['date'].append(date.text)
                #print(date.text)

        #get platform
        table_rows = content[tblnum].find_all('tr')
        for tr in table_rows:
            td = tr.find_all('td')
            for platform in td[1].find_all('span',{"class":"data"}):
                data_dict['platform'].append(platform.text.strip())
                #print(platform.text.strip())

        #get Game score
        table_rows = content[tblnum].find_all('tr')
        for tr in table_rows:
            td = tr.find_all('td')
            for user in td[0].find_all('div',{"class":"metascore_w"}):
                data_dict['score'].append(user.text.strip())
                #print(user.text.strip())

        #getting game url
        table_rows = content[tblnum].find_all('tr')
        for tr in table_rows:
            td = tr.find_all('td')
            for a in td[1].find_all('a', {"class":"title"} ,href=True):
                data_dict['url'].append(a['href'])
                #print(a['href'])

        #get Game userscore
        table_rows = content[tblnum].find_all('tr')
        for tr in table_rows:
            td = tr.find_all('td')
            for score in td[1].find_all('div', {"class":"metascore_w"}):
                data_dict['userscore'].append(score.text)
                #print(score.text)
        tblnum += 1

def pages(lastPageNum, year): #Function that returns the html(code) and initiates the web scrapper
    currentPage = 0
    while currentPage < int(lastPageNum):
        url = url = 'https://www.metacritic.com/browse/games/score/metascore/year/all/filtered?year_selected='+ str(year) +'&distribution=&sort=desc&view=condensed&page=' + str(currentPage)
        userAgent = {'User-agent': 'Mozilla/5.0'}
        response = requests.get(url, headers=userAgent)
        soup = BeautifulSoup(response.text, 'html.parser')
        content = soup.find_all('table')

        num_loops = len(content)
        #print(num_loops)
        scrapper(num_loops,content)
        #print(data_dict)
        currentPage += 1
        #print(currentPage)
        time.sleep(6)

def is_integer(n):
    try:
        float(n)
    except ValueError:
        return False
    else:
        return float(n).is_integer()
        
def main():
    years = list(range(2000,2021)) # Year
    for year in years:
        numPage = (numberPages(webpage(0,year)))
        if (numPage == 0 or numPage is None or not is_integer(numPage)):
            print("No data")
        else:
            pages(int(numPage),year)
            time.sleep(5)
            # print(year)
    xData = (pd.DataFrame.from_dict(data_dict))
    xData.to_csv('mc.csv')

# file1= open("sample_html","w")
# file1.write(webpage(0,2020).text)
# file1.close()
# #print(webpage(0,2020).text)
main()

Data Tidying¶

Now that we have all three tables, we can tidy them up individually by deciding how to deal with missing values and then joining them based on video game title. First, we will look at how to deal with the missing user reviews from the metacritic data. After that, we will review the VGChartz dataset missing sales data. Lastly, we will review The HLTB.com dataset to see if any of the games that have missing completion times are in the primary metacritic dataset. We are doing an inner join between the two, so fining the missing data should be easy.

Tidying Metacritic dataset¶

The best course of action for the missing user reviews in the metacritic dataset is to convert them to NaN to prevent errors. Since critic score is never missing, we will only have to review the user score column.

Tidying VGChartz dataset¶

The VGChartz has a lot of missing data since, as stated before, not all developers release sales metrics publicly. If a title does not have US Sales metrics, I will be dropping it so that I am not introducing any bias by digging deeper into certain popular titles to fill in missing data. These entries will be Missing at random since their missingness is attributed to the publisher's choice and is out of my control. There are also some entries with missing developer data, but there is always a publisher. We will also be fixing platform names so that they match between the datasets when we join.

Tidying HLTB dataset¶

The HLTB has a lot of missing data because of it being an open source site where anyone can upload their completion times to certain games, published or not. Since we will be focusing on games that have a completion time (to determine if that has an affect on sales), we will be dropping any entries that do not have a completion time (these are usually multiplayer only DLCs and mods, which do not effect the base game's sales).

Data Visualization and Analysis¶

Now that our data is all together and separated into frames that have had their missing data dealt with, we can begin attempting to find trends in what makes a video game sell well. We will start by doing a simple plot of sales over time between consoles.

Our dependent variables are:

  • Sales (USD)
  • Critic Score

Our independent variables are:

  • Release date
  • Genre
  • Time to beat
  • Platform

First, we will start by analyzing the raw VGChartz data to find what platforms sell the best over time.

Analysis¶

The plot above shows sales numbers grouped by platforms where each platform has a different shape and each "generation" of platform has a different color as shown in the legend. This plot shows us four things:

  1. Given the regression line, there is no strong relationship between release year and sales. This does not nullify the possibility of a relationship between time of year and sales, which we will look at next.
  2. More games after 2008 sold well on average than pre-2008. More games make over 3 million in sales as compared to in 2002 and 2003 there were only 2 games that got past 3 million sales.
  3. Most of the games that sell the best are released on either a Playstation 3/4 or Xbox 360/One (The major consoles). You are most likely to succeed by releasing your game on either of these consoles (or both!).
  4. It seems that there are always higher sales towards the end of the year when compared to the beginning. For example, look at late 2013 and you can see many games selling well around the same time creating a vertical line.

We will look deeper into this trend by binning our data by release quarters and standardize the values across the years using seaborn violin plot to show relative game performance based on quarter. Q1: Jan, Feb, Mar Q2: Apr, May, Jun Q3: Jul, Aug, Sep Q4: Oct, Nov, Dec

I am expecting to see higher average sales in Q4 across all years.

Analysis¶

Here we can see a slightly different trend for release month of a video game. Video games that sell well tend to be in quarter 4. The most mid-heavy plots seem to be February, March, and December, meaning that video games released in these times do not sell too well. The plots with the highest means are April, September, October, and November, making these the best months to release a video game. November makes the most sense since most people purchase their gifts for Christmas around that time. Video game sales seem to follow seasons. April is around when Summer starts in some states, boosting sales, and then October is about when Winter starts, giving people more time inside to play video games. Then November is the holiday season, boosting gifted video game sales. December does not likely sell well because most of the sales were collected in November. Releasing a video game in December likely misses the sales rush and is not efficient.

Lets try to form a linear regression based on release month.

Analysis¶

As expected, there is no clear trend between the time to beat a game and sales. You can make a game that takes over 100 hours to beat, but still sell far less than a million copies. This means that the biggest effect on sales are release date and critic scores.

Most best sellers have around 10 hours of playtime, which is a decent length for a game. After 50 hours, games are not likely to sell well. Personally, I find that 30 hours is the sweet spot for a good story rich game.

Just to make sure we are not missing any relationship, we will calculate the P-Value.

Analysis¶

The P-Value of the residual model is 0.000951, which is fairly high. This means that the null hypothesis of no relationship is true for playtime vs sales.

Conclusion¶

At this point, it is clear that the biggest factor that we have looked at that results in video games doing well is release date and rating. The best release month is October, which will collect holiday sales from November and December. Getting a critic score of above 80 will also result in increased sales on average. The amount of time it takes to beat a game has little efect on sales, but having a game too short (<5 hours) or too long (>50 hours) can have negative effects on sales. Lastly, action-adventure and shooter are the most popular genres in the last 20 years, which means they are the best games to make if you want to appeal to the largest audience.

Final Thoughts¶

While I did not have time to get into more metrics that effect success such as advertising, "hype," controversy, and sales, it is still possible to measure these metrics, albiet far more work.

To measure advertising, a new dataset would have to be made that tracks a games advertising budget (For example, Cyberpunk 2077 had an advertising budget of 1.2 billion PLN or roughly $316,131,480 USD, and it sold extremely well despite having bad ratings). This dataset would need a lot of work and research since advertising budget is not often public.

Measuring video game "hype" and controversy is a little trickier, requiring more assumptions and language processing. Tracking trending Twitter hashtags is one way to find if a game is hyped. Monitoring subreddit activity for a game's subreddit (if one exists) or looking at the number of posts that are made about a game is another great way to track hype. Games that are hyped will very often have a lot of popular posts with their trailers and gameplay shots. Controversy is similar, but would require searching for key words in relation to a game's posts like "disappointing," "worst game ever," "this is why I don't preorder," and so on.

The last metric I wanted to look at but did not have time is the effect of christmas sales on video game sales. Does putting a video game on sale during the holidays for \$10 off result in a significant increase in sales when compared to games that do not go on sale. What is the best price for a video game? Is \\$60 too much? These are questions that you, the reader can answer, by just doing more digging into datasets or making your own!

Another interesting topic to cover is the effect of COVID-19 on video game sales, given that more people are at home.
